statement:
Consider the matrix

\begin{align*}
A=\begin{bmatrix}
3  &  2\\
2  &  3
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

Use
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2012/Question_4_(c)}{part
(c)} to explicitly compute $A^k$ for any positive integer k.

sols:
From
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2012/Question_4_(c)}{part
(c)}, we have that $\displaystyle A = MDM^{-1}$ where

\[M = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
-1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}\]

\[M^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix}
1/2  &  -1/2\\
1/2  &  1/2
\end{bmatrix}\]

and

\[D = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 5
\end{bmatrix}\]

Taking powers yields

\begin{align*}
A^{k} &= (MDM^{-1})^k \\
&= MDM^{-1} \cdot MDM^{-1}\cdot \ldots \cdot MDM^{-1} \\
&= MD^{k}M^{-1} \\
&= \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
-1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 5^{k}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1/2 & -1/2 \\
1/2 & 1/2
\end{bmatrix} \\
&= \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\begin{bmatrix}
1 +5^{k} & -1 + 5^{k} \\
-1 +5^{k} & 1 + 5^{k}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}
